    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "* 2. Show *for-all* statements: take arbitrary values\n\nLet us consider the following lemma."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "Lemma every_x_equal_to_itself :\n  for all x : ℝ,\n    x = x."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "> #<strong>#NOTE:#</strong># the notation $x : ℝ$ means $x$ is in $\\mathbb{R}$ (or more accurately, $x$ is of type $\\mathbb{R}$) may be unfamiliar to you, and you may be more familiar with the notation $x ∈ \\reals$. This difference is due to the fact that Waterproof is built on #<strong>#type theory#</strong># and not on set theory. \n\n#<strong>#HINT:#</strong># You can insert characters such as ℝ either from the symbol menu that opens when clicking on 'Σ' in the top right corner, or you can write '\\reals' until a menu pops up and press enter. Make sure that the code reads 'ℝ' and not '\\reals' itself. For many other unicode characters you can use a backslash command as well."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "\nProof."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "\nTo show a statement like \"for all $x : \\mathbb{R}$, ...\", you first need to take an arbitrary $x : \\mathbb{R}$, and then continue showing ... . We do this by writing and executing the following sentence, i.e. by applying the following #<strong>#tactic#</strong>#."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "\nTake x : ℝ."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "\nWhen showing $∀ x : ℝ, ...$, after taking $x : \\mathbb{R}$ we need to continue showing whatever statement is at the place of the dots $...$. In our case, we need to show that $x = x$. So we are back in a situation we are by now familiar with. We finish the proof as before."
    },
    {
      "type": "code",
      "text": "\nWe conclude that (x = x).\nQed."
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "text": "** Try it yourself: show *for-all* statements\n\nTry to complete the proof of the following lemma."
    },
